The report found the changes will simply ensure there is more credit available during the economic recovery without undermining consumer protection. It will sweep away duplication and provide clearer consumer protections.

I am a markets person, but there is regulation in every market. Big Tech is the Wild West and this is a proportionate response designed to bring parties to the table which I am confident it will do. We won’t yield to threats. We can’t.
Facebook, which is the home of fake news, told the committee that credible news from the ABC, Australian or Guardian had no commercial value!

The bottom line is that while Google’s threats to consumers and policy makers sounds bad, their solution “Showcase” remains a column of smoke. This is the credibility gap. I have asked Google to provide details of Showcase on notice to the @auSenate.

Only a few months ago the US Congressional report recommended a similar pathway. There would be very few regulated companies in Australia if every company left when a new regulation came into force. Even the cigarette companies didn’t leave over Aust-first plain packaging laws!

Google would be withdrawing from many, many markets if there was to be a requirement for technology companies to pay for journalism. Threatening to leave Australia is occurring because Australia is a leading jurisdiction but one of many which is looking at these problems.

Now Google threatens to leave Australia by effectively blackmailing consumers and policy makers if they cannot use Showcase - which we have never seen. The dynamics in Australia are similar to other markets.

Google says it wants to use “Google Showcase” to pay for journalism. This would obviate the need for the code as the legislation sets out but “Showcase” isn’t available in Australia, which makes it a column of smoke. This doesn’t appear to be a serious attempt to engage.

Google don’t want to pay for “links and snippets” which is not mentioned in the legislation but seems to be central to the business model where media outfits have seen their advertising revenue move to Big Tech. This would appear to gut the code.

Unlike telcos, banks or power companies, Big Tech don’t have minimum service standards, licensing, capital requirements or dispute resolution arrangements. They generate large sums of revenue but pay a very low level of tax in Australia.

The difference between media outfits and a coffee shop on Google is that the barista gets paid for their coffee whereas the media content is repurposed onto Google which collects advertising revenue instead of the media outfit.

The whole basis of this reform is to ensure public interest journalism has a viable future in Australia. This is in response to the collection of advertising revenue by tech companies rather than media companies, thereby threatening the future of public interest journalism.

John Moriarty speaks in detail about the creation of the flag by Harold Thomas in the early 1970s and appears to be in possession of an original design prototype which he has agreed to table.
